[[Image:Hemingray42.jpg|thumb|150px|The Hemingray 42, a telegraph insulator produced by the Hemingray Glass Company, is widely found in North America]] The '''Hemingray Glass Company''' was an [[United States|American]] [[glass]] manufacturing [[company]]. The company was founded by Robert Hemingray and Ralph Gray in [[Cincinnati]] in 1848.<ref name="glassbottlemarks"/> In its early years the company went through numerous and frequent name changes, including Gray & Hemingray; Gray, Hemingray & Bros.; Gray, Hemingray & Brother; Hemingray Bros. & Company and R. Hemingray & Company before incorporating into the Hemingray Glass Company, Inc in 1870.<ref name="glassbottlemarks">{{cite web |url= http://www.glassbottlemarks.com/hemingray/ |title=Hemingray Glass Company |first=David |last=Whitten |work=glassbottlemarks.com |year=2015 |accessdate=May 25, 2015}}</ref> The Hemingray company had factories in [[Cincinnati, Ohio]] and [[Covington, Kentucky]] with main production in [[Muncie, Indiana]]. Though Hemingray was best known for its [[telegraph]] insulators, the company produced many other glass items including [[bottle]]s, [[Mason jar|fruit jars]], pressed glass [[plate (dishware)|dishes]], [[List of glassware#tumblers|tumblers]], [[battery (electricity)|battery]] jars, [[aquarium|fishbowls]], [[lantern|lantern globes]], and [[oil lamp]]s.<ref name="glassbottlemarks"/> In 1933, the company was sold to the [[Owens-Illinois Glass Company]] but production remained in Muncie under the Hemingray name.
The main plant in Muncie shut down in 1966<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.insulators.info/articles/hemi100.htm |title=Hemingray Glass Insulators - 100 Years Of History |first=Bill |last=Meier |work=insulators.info |year=2011 |accessdate=May 25, 2015}}</ref> and insulator production ceased. The complex is now the used by [[Gerdau]] Ameristeel, a steel production company headquartered in [[Brazil]].
==Insulators== Hemingray was best known for producing telegraph insulators. To give an overview of the large variety of styles produced, the following table contains the twenty most common.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.hemingray.info/database/top20.php |title=Hemingray.info - The Hemingray Database: Top 20 Identified Insulators |first=Christian |last=Willis |work=hemingray.info |year=2015 |accessdate=May 25, 2015}}</ref> There are two numbers given in this table: the Consolidated Design (CD) number and the style number. The CD number is from a classification system developed by collectors that refers to the shape of the insulator and is completely independent from the Hemingray Glass Company.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.insulators.info/general/cdnumber.htm |title=CD Numbers Explained |first=Bill |last=Meier |work=insulators.info |year=2010 |accessdate=May 25, 2015}}</ref> However the style number (or name) was assigned by Hemingray to each insulator. Due to slight modifications in design over years of production single styles can span multiple CD numbers.
