The '''pin-point method''' (or point-intercept method) is used for [[non-destructive]] measurements of [[plant cover]] and plant [[biomass]].<ref name=Coker>{{cite book|quotes= |last=Coker|first= Kent A.|author2=Coker, P. |year= 1992 |title= Vegetation Description and Analysis&nbsp;– A Practical Approach |publisher= John Wiley |location = New York}}</ref><ref name=Jonasson>{{cite journal |quotes= |last=Jonasson|first= Sven |year= 1988 |title= Evaluation of the Point Intercept Method for the Estimation of Plant Biomass |journal= Oikos |volume= 52|issue= |pages= 101–106 |doi=10.2307/3565988}}</ref>
In a pin-point analysis, a frame (or a [[transect]]) with a fixed [[grid pattern]] is placed above the vegetation. A pin is inserted vertically through one of the grid points into the vegetation and will typically touch a number of plants. The number of times the pin touches different plant species is then recorded. This procedure is repeated at each grid point. Vertical rulers connected to the frame are used to prevent horizontal drift of the pins and to measure the height of vegetation hit by the pins.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Heady|first=Harold F.|last2=Rader|first2=Lynn|date=March 1958|title=Modifications of the Point Frame|url=|journal=Journal of Range Management|volume=11|issue=2|pages=2|doi=10.2307/3894295}}</ref>
